    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 18 with a lineup anchored by the high-upside profile of **Yordan Alvarez** (77.33), who draws an favorable matchup against Andre Pallante. While **Yordan Alvarez** faces a mid-tier SP_xERA, his elite contact metrics make him our primary offensive engine. Joining him as a priority start is **Hyeseong Kim** (70.16), whose value is inflated by a dream matchup against Ryan Feltner. Not only does **Hyeseong Kim** benefit from a park factor boost, but the prospect of facing a slow-delivery pitcher creates an opportunistic environment for him to swipe bags\u2014a critical factor given our league's scarcity of stolen bases. Similarly, **Colt Keith** (68.51) and **Carson Benge** (67.06) capitalize on platoon advantages and favorable park conditions, making them high-confidence plays to anchor our mid-order production.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, who finished just outside the starting cut at 46.11. Despite his solid raw projections, **Jerar Encarnacion** ultimately lost out to the specialized utility roles of **Junior Caminero** (53.51) and **Chase Meidroth** (52.55). While **Junior Caminero** faces a daunting task against Paul Skenes, his positional versatility and potential for extra-base hits in a high-leverage spot provided enough value to edge out the bench. We are also monitoring the extreme difficulty of the pitching matchups for **Trea Turner** and **Kyle Schwarber**, both of whom are facing the elite Chris Sale. While both maintain acceptable daily efficiency scores, their output will be heavily dependent on their ability to overcome Sale's 2.88 xERA, which significantly drags down their otherwise strong baseline projections.\n\nInvestors should note that today\u2019s lineup remains speculative as official cards are still pending. We have relied on historical batting order trends for players like **Dillon Dingler**, **Gary Sanchez**, and **Victor Scott II**, but any late-hour lineup shuffling\u2014particularly for **Victor Scott II** or **Pete Crow-Armstrong**\u2014could shift their stolen base efficiency windows. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** remains a high-variance play; while he faces the formidable Freddy Peralta, his 92% steal efficiency and the positive platoon split provide enough of an edge to warrant the start. Managers should keep a close eye on weather reports, as the current projections assume standard conditions across all parks.",
